{"type":"message","id":"8f6727c6","parentId":"8f23ab99","timestamp":"2026-05-03T21:04:32.604Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting. So the state file exists at the wiki root, not in the sessions directory. The mtime of the finn jsonl file is `1777781420.4420278` and the state file has `finn_jsonl_mtime: 1777781420.4420278`. These match exactly - so the script correctly reports \"No new messages for finn\".\n\nBut wait, the jsonl file is 38KB and hasn't been modified since May 3 00:10. Let me check if the state file's timestamp matches the actual file's mtime exactly. The stat shows `May  3 00:10:20 2026` and the state has `1777781420.4420278`. \n\nLet me convert that unix timestamp: 1777781420 seconds since epoch. \n\nSince the script only logs new messages when the mtime changes, and this file hasn't been modified since early morning on May 3rd, there genuinely haven't been any new messages. But wait - the cron job is running right now, so shouldn't there be new messages? Let me check the current session in use. Looking back at the session data, the most recent run ended at timestamp 1777781420443 (May 3, 2026 00:10:20 UTC), which matches the jsonl file's mtime exactly.\n\nThe session status shows as \"done\" with a 15-second runtime, but the file hasn't been modified since then. That's odd - usually new interactions would create new entries in the jsonl file. Unless the cron job itself triggers a new session that writes to the same file, updating the mtime. But the timestamp matches exactly between the session data and the file, so either this cron already ran and wrote the same mtime, or the jsonl file is stale and doesn't reflect new activity in the current session. The jsonl file on disk hasn't been touched since May 3 at midnight, even though the session record says it was last modified at 00:10. This discrepancy suggests the file either wasn't actually updated when the session ended, or something went wrong with